(PEH, 12/21/93)
The "sim" program was copied from Tom Lookabaugh's (backed-up)
home directory.  These files were taken from
	/data/mir1/toml_home/devel/timing


(PEH, 12/30/93)
The "timing" program was created separately, using Tom's code
as a starting point.  The results of the timing program
match well with the results predicted by Tom in CLI-92-0006.
-	At a 10Hz timestamp rate, w/ a 16-tap FIR loop filter,
	the settling time is about 5 seconds
-	The steady-state error with the above conditions is on the
	order of 3 Hz (out of 27 MHz).
-	The steady-state error and settling time are mostly unaffected
	by jitter in the timestamp sample times.  We vary the timestamp
	sampling times uniformly in the range
	(0, 2*nominal_inter_timestamp_time) with no appreciable degradation
	in performance as compared to the situation in which all
	inter-timestamp times are fixed at the nominal value.

(PEH, 3/23/94)
This directory now contains some Matlab *.m files useful in
analyzing feedback PLL systems:
-	loopdenom.m return the denominator of the PLL closed-loop
	transfer function, given the FIR loop filter taps and loop gain
-	loopxfer.m gives the FFT of the PLL closed-loop transfer 
	function, given the FIR loop filter taps and loop gain.
-	maxp.m gives the magnitude of the largest pole of the PLL
	closed-loop transfer function, given the FIR loop filter taps and
	the loop gain.
-	rect.m returns the taps of a unity-gain FIR rectangular filter of
	a given length.
-	pllnoise.m gives the integral of the power spectral density of
	the VCO input of a PLL system.  The square root of this value 
	multiplied by the input noise standard deviation gives the
	standard deviation of the steady-state PLL frequency error.
-	pllacquire.m gives the ramp response (at VCO input) of a PLL.
	This can be used to calculate the acquisition time of a PLL.

(PEH, 3/23/94)
The "timing" program has been modified to implement "multistep"
timing acquisition and recovery.  See the source code or my journal
for details.
